<SiteLayout
  site="westmount"
  title="Options Trading for Beginners: A Complete Guide"
  description="Options can hedge your portfolio or blow it up — the difference is understanding the Greeks. A jargon-free guide from calls and puts to real strategies."
  canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/guide-options-basics" schema={schema}
>


<div class="header">
    <span class="tag">Educational Guide</span>
    <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-[var(--accent-color)] mb-6 text-center">Options Trading for Beginners</h1>
    <p style="color: #6a7a90; max-width: 600px; margin: 0 auto;">A clear, jargon-free introduction to calls, puts, strategies, the Greeks, and how to manage risk.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-6 py-12">
    <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">Options trading can seem like a complex maze of mathematical formulas and confusing jargon. But at its core, an option is simply a contract that gives you choices. This guide will break down the essential concepts of options trading into plain English, helping you understand how they work and how they can be used strategically.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-8 mb-4">1. What Are Options? Calls vs. Puts</h2>
    <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">An option is a contract tied to an underlying asset (like a stock) that gives the buyer the right—but not the obligation—to buy or sell that asset at a specific price on or before a specific date.</p>

    <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
      <h4>Call Options (The Right to Buy)</h4>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">A call option gives you the right to <strong>buy</strong> a stock at a predetermined price. You typically buy a call when you believe a stock's price will go up.</p>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><em>Analogy:</em> Placing a deposit to lock in the price of a house before deciding to buy it.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
      <h4>Put Options (The Right to Sell)</h4>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">A put option gives you the right to <strong>sell</strong> a stock at a predetermined price. You typically buy a put when you believe a stock's price will go down, or to protect a stock you already own.</p>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><em>Analogy:</em> Buying insurance on your car. If the car's value drops (it gets damaged), the insurance protects you.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-8 mb-4">2. Key Terms You Need to Know</h2>
    <ul>
      <li class="mb-2 text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Strike Price:</strong> The predetermined price at which the option can be exercised (buying or selling the underlying stock).</li>
      <li class="mb-2 text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Premium:</strong> The price you pay to buy the option contract. If you sell an option, the premium is the money you receive.</li>
      <li class="mb-2 text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Expiration Date:</strong> The date the contract expires. If you haven't used your option by this date, it ceases to exist.</li>
      <li class="mb-2 text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Multiplier:</strong> Standard equity options represent 100 shares of the underlying stock. If an option's premium is quoted at $2.00, it actually costs $200 ($2.00 x 100 shares).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-xl font-bold text-white mt-6 mb-2">Moneyness (ITM, ATM, OTM)</h3>
    <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">Moneyness describes the relationship between the stock's current price and the option's strike price:</p>
    <table class="w-full border-collapse bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl overflow-hidden text-left mb-6">
      <tr>
        <th class="p-4 font-semibold text-white border-b border-[var(--border-color)]">Term</th>
        <th class="p-4 font-semibold text-white border-b border-[var(--border-color)]">Meaning</th>
        <th class="p-4 font-semibold text-white border-b border-[var(--border-color)]">For a Call Option</th>
        <th class="p-4 font-semibold text-white border-b border-[var(--border-color)]">For a Put Option</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="p-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>In-The-Money (ITM)</strong></td>
        <td class="p-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] text-[var(--text-secondary)]">The option has intrinsic value.</td>
        <td class="p-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Stock price > Strike price</td>
        <td class="p-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Stock price &lt; Strike price</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="p-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>At-The-Money (ATM)</strong></td>
        <td class="p-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Strike price equals the current stock price.</td>
        <td class="p-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Stock price = Strike price</td>
        <td class="p-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Stock price = Strike price</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="p-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Out-Of-The-Money (OTM)</strong></td>
        <td class="p-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] text-[var(--text-secondary)]">The option currently has no intrinsic value, only time value.</td>
        <td class="p-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Stock price &lt; Strike price</td>
        <td class="p-4 border-b border-[var(--border-color)] text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Stock price > Strike price</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-8 mb-4">3. Buying vs. Selling (Writing) Options</h2>
    <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">Every options trade has two sides: a buyer and a seller.</p>
    <ul>
      <li class="mb-2 text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Option Buyers:</strong> Pay a premium for the <em>right</em> to buy or sell. Their risk is limited to the premium paid, but their profit potential can be theoretically unlimited (for calls) or very high (for puts).</li>
      <li class="mb-2 text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Option Sellers (Writers):</strong> Receive a premium but take on the <em>obligation</em> to buy or sell if the buyer exercises their right. Their profit is limited to the premium received, but their risk can be substantial if the trade goes against them.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-8 mb-4">4. The 4 Basic Positions</h2>
    <div class="greeks-grid">
      <div class="greek-card">
        <div class="greek-name">1. Long Call</div>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Action:</strong> Buying a call option.</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>View:</strong> Bullish (you want the stock to rise).</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Risk:</strong> Limited to premium paid.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="greek-card">
        <div class="greek-name">2. Long Put</div>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Action:</strong> Buying a put option.</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>View:</strong> Bearish (you want the stock to fall).</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Risk:</strong> Limited to premium paid.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="greek-card">
        <div class="greek-name">3. Short Call</div>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Action:</strong> Selling a call option.</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>View:</strong> Bearish/Neutral (you want the stock to stay flat or fall).</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Risk:</strong> Theoretically unlimited.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="greek-card">
        <div class="greek-name">4. Short Put</div>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Action:</strong> Selling a put option.</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>View:</strong> Bullish/Neutral (you want the stock to stay flat or rise).</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Risk:</strong> Substantial (stock could go to zero).</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-8 mb-4">5. Common Beginner Strategies</h2>
    <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">Once you understand the basic positions, you can combine them with owning shares to create strategies with defined risk profiles.</p>

    <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
      <h4>Covered Call</h4>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">You own 100 shares of a stock and sell 1 call option against those shares. You collect the premium, which generates income. If the stock rises past the strike price, you will be obligated to sell your shares at that strike price.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
      <h4>Protective Put</h4>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">You own shares of a stock and buy a put option. This acts like an insurance policy. If the stock crashes, your put option gains value, offsetting your losses on the shares. The cost of this "insurance" is the premium you pay.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
      <h4>Cash-Secured Put</h4>
      <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">You want to buy a stock, but at a lower price than it currently trades. You sell a put option at your desired strike price and set aside the cash to buy the shares. You collect the premium upfront. If the stock drops below the strike price, you are obligated to buy the shares (which you wanted to do anyway). If it stays above, you simply keep the premium.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-8 mb-4">6. The Greeks: Intuitive Explanations</h2>
    <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">Option prices don't move 1-to-1 with stock prices. "The Greeks" are mathematical metrics that estimate how much an option's price will change based on different variables.</p>

    <div class="greeks-grid">
      <div class="greek-card">
        <div class="greek-name">Delta (Δ)</div>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>What it measures:</strong> Price movement.</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Intuition:</strong> If the stock moves by $1.00, how much will the option price change? A delta of 0.50 means the option price will move about $0.50 for every $1.00 move in the stock.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="greek-card">
        <div class="greek-name">Gamma (Γ)</div>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>What it measures:</strong> The speed of Delta.</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Intuition:</strong> As the stock price moves, Delta changes. Gamma tells you how fast Delta is accelerating or decelerating.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="greek-card">
        <div class="greek-name">Theta (Θ)</div>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>What it measures:</strong> Time decay.</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Intuition:</strong> Options are wasting assets. Theta tells you how much value the option loses every single day just because time has passed, assuming all else stays the same.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="greek-card">
        <div class="greek-name">Vega (ν)</div>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>What it measures:</strong> Volatility impact.</p>
        <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed"><strong>Intuition:</strong> When the market gets scared or excited, option prices inflate. Vega measures how much the option price will increase or decrease with a 1% change in implied volatility.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-8 mb-4">7. Time Decay and Expiration</h2>
    <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">One of the hardest lessons for new traders is understanding that <strong>most options expire worthless.</strong></p>
    <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">Unlike buying a stock, which you can hold forever waiting for a turnaround, an option is a ticking clock. Because of Theta (time decay), an option loses a tiny bit of value every day. This decay accelerates rapidly in the final 30 days before expiration.</p>
    <p class="text-[var(--text-secondary)] mb-4 leading-relaxed">If you buy a Call option because you think a stock will go up, but the stock stays completely flat for a month, your option will lose value. You don't just have to be right about direction; you have to be right about direction <strong>and</strong> timing.</p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-8 mb-4">8. Risk Management Rules</h2>
    <ul>
      <li class="mb-2 text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Never risk money you can't afford to lose:</strong> Option buying can result in a 100% loss of the premium paid.</li>
      <li class="mb-2 text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Start small:</strong> Trade one contract at a time while you are learning.</li>
      <li class="mb-2 text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Avoid naked selling:</strong> Never sell a "naked" call or put unless you fully understand and can afford the massive risks involved. Stick to covered calls and cash-secured puts.</li>
      <li class="mb-2 text-[var(--text-secondary)]"><strong>Understand Implied Volatility:</strong> Avoid buying options right before earnings reports when premiums are highly inflated (high Vega) and will suffer from a "volatility crush" the next day.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mt-8 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="mb-6 bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-6 rounded-xl">
      <div class="text-lg mb-3 text-white font-bold">What is the difference between buying and selling an option?</div>
      <div class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Buying an option gives you the right (but not the obligation) to buy or sell a stock at a specific price. Selling (or writing) an option obligates you to buy or sell the stock if the buyer chooses to exercise their right.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="mb-6 bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-6 rounded-xl">
      <div class="text-lg mb-3 text-white font-bold">Can I lose more money than I invest in options?</div>
      <div class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">If you are buying options (long calls or long puts), your maximum loss is strictly limited to the premium you paid. However, if you are selling (writing) 'naked' options, your potential losses can be substantial or theoretically unlimited.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="mb-6 bg-[var(--card-bg)] border border-[var(--border-color)] p-6 rounded-xl">
      <div class="text-lg mb-3 text-white font-bold">Why do options expire worthless?</div>
      <div class="text-[var(--text-secondary)]">Options have a limited lifespan. Because of a concept called time decay, an option loses value as it approaches its expiration date. If the stock price doesn't move past the option's strike price before expiration, the option will have no value.</div>
    </div>

  </div>

  
